@startuml AgentTalk-MCP-Topology
title AgentTalk MCP Orchestration — Topology A (Node is the MCP server)

skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam shadowing false

actor "Reviewer\n(web UI)" as UI

package "Node orchestrator (AgentTalk)" {
  [Registry / TeamCoordinator\nhandleMcpToolCall()] as REG
  [AgentTalk MCP Server\nWebSocket /mcp\ntools: send_to_agent, submit_plan,\nagreement_*, submit_work_*, ...] as MCP
  REG <--> MCP : injects tool schemas + handlers
}

UI <--> REG : observability

package "codex CLI process" {
  [codex\n(MCP client)] as CODEX
  [mcp-bridge\nstdio <-> WS] as BC
  CODEX --> BC : stdio JSON-RPC
}

package "claude CLI process" {
  [claude\n(MCP client)] as CLAUDE
  [mcp-bridge\nstdio <-> WS] as BCL
  CLAUDE --> BCL : stdio JSON-RPC
}

package "gemini CLI process" {
  [gemini\n(MCP client)] as GEM
  [mcp-bridge\nstdio <-> WS] as BG
  GEM --> BG : stdio JSON-RPC
}

BC  --> MCP : WebSocket  ?agentId=codex
BCL --> MCP : WebSocket  ?agentId=claude
BG  --> MCP : WebSocket  ?agentId=gemini

note bottom of MCP
  **AgentTalk is the MCP server.** Each CLI connects IN as an MCP **client**
  (via a stdio->WebSocket bridge). The model running inside the CLI **calls
  AgentTalk's tools** instead of printing [AgentTalk]: lines on stdout.
  Per-agent isolation: the agentId query param maps each socket to its session.
end note

legend right
  Arrows point client -> server (direction of connection).
  Transport: stdio (CLI<->bridge) then WebSocket (bridge<->AgentTalk).
  See design/mcp-orchestration-proposal.md sections 4 and 11A.
endlegend
@enduml
